reviewText:
After a lot of hours put into this masterpiece (and after I hopefully started to understand most of the lore behind the Bad Rats universe), I think I am ready to write a review for Bad Rats.
Personally, the best feeling I had while playing this game was blowing up cats and finding strategic ways to do it.
There are many rats to choose from, my favorite one being the terrorrat, a rat desperately wanting to blow itself up. Players who don't like this playing style, but generally want to play with the terrorrat will be happy to see that Bad Rats has a variety of different rats. If you want, for example, a rocketrat, it will be, of course, harder work than for a vaccumrat, but as much rewarding, because you will notice how your character truly evolves during Bad Rats. You have tons of options, tons of playing styles (which you can mix or even change at any point in the game if you feel like it).
But enough with characters. Other aspect which really felt unique and incredible was the size of the game. Not only Bad Rats itself is huge, considerably one of the biggest levels seen in a video game, but it's also fullfilled with things to do. I never went from one hold to another without finding plenty of puzzles, rats, cats into my way. And, if you're like me, you don't want to rush through the main story and prefer instead to explore more or do miscellaneous cat hunting, you'll be glad to take the side rats whenever you see them. The exploration never had an end for me, not even after so many hours spent into the game.
You are probably curious about the cat system. While technically not one of the best I have seen in a Rat game, I must admit that it had massively been improved since The game launch. The ''Luck'' factor is not present any more, so you can't miss a shot when you clearly were very close to the cat. The third person camera is now immersive, with tons of new animations and a new feature which I like a lot: the ratcam.
One final aspect I'd like to talk about is the length of the game. While the main storyline is relatively short (took me around 10 hours on hardest difficulty), the side cat destroying levels and rat quests make this game incredibly long. If you get Bad rats and plan on beating every single level, clearing every cat, finding every way to kill the cat, you'd better get prepared for a very, VERY long journey. I myself haven't completed a quarter of the entire game yet (checked progress with a mod).
This game is by far my favorite Rat game at the time being, its biggest rival in my opinion being Hello Kitty: The game.
Pros: + incredibly large levels, mixing bioms from brick walls to imersive indoor walls.
+ a lot of locations, free for player to explore; hundreds of rat holes, which at their turn are themselves long and filled with cats, puzzles, traps which will reward handsomely the player at the end;
+ plenty of cat hunting, most of which don't require the player to have completed the main questline;
+ the introduction of cats as enemies, for the first time in the bad rats game;
+ residents of bad rats all have their own lives and families. In the morning, they will leave their cat hunting and go to their job, in the afternoon they will take a break for eating, and in the evening they will close their shop and go back to their home or at the inn for some mead, where after a few hours will go to sleep;
+ random encounters will let the rat find more about the game; fugitives will tell you to keep their stolen rats for a short while, followed by a scene where the owner finds you and asks you whether you have seen the thief (at this point, you can lie, you can tell him where the thief went, or you can be most honest and give him his rat); couriers will once in a while give the corespondence to you, which can lead to impressive new cat killing or will update your levels with new rats.
+ the leveling system has been improved since Its launch: after you have a high level, you will no longer see ALL cats with the same killing animation, instead you will continue to find better and bigger cat killing animations;
+ rats can buy home in 5 holds, where he can place his cat bodies, take his wife and kids and take a rest; this, personally, felt like a huge immersive feature in the bad rats
+ you feel that your rat truly evolves as you progress; more over, you can make what you want of your rat: a good terrorrat, archerrat, smokingrat, etc., by using your skills;
Cons: - interface is worse than at launch; you can't sort items by criterias (feature that had been available in Hello Kitty: The game), you can't search for a specific item when you have plenty of rats in your inventory, and the aspect is generally bad; thus i recommend using a mod that changes inventory;
- while reasonable, the game is filled with bugs, some of which can even break a level; again, i recommend using the Unofficial Patches;
- some textures and meshes haven't been vigurously worked by developers and they look bad for 2009;

Personal rating: 95/100
